Lycidas.

Weep no more, woful shepherds, weep no more, For Lycidas your sorrow is not dead,

Sunk though he be beneath the watery floor3

So sinks the day-star in the ocean-hed,

And yet anon repairs his drooping head,

And tricks his beamS, and with new-spangled ore Flames in the forehead of the morning shy:

Dirge.

F ear no more the heat o’ the sun, Nor the furious winter’s rages: Thou thy worldly task host done, Home art gone, and ta’en thy weges.

Golden lads and girls all must, As chimney-sweepers, come to dust.

Fear no more the frown o' the great; Thou art past the tyrant’s stroke: Care no more to clotho and eat3 To thee the reed is as the oak. The sceptre, learning, physic, must All follow this, and come to dust.
